THE MOSELLE

9⁷ Nor shall I pass thee by, O Salmon, with flesh of rosy red, the random strokes of whose broad tail from the mid—depths are reproduced upon the sui-face, when the still water’s face betrays thy hidden course. Thou, with breastplate of scales, in the fore-part smooth, and destined to form a course at some “doubtful dinner,'’1 endurest untainted through seasons of long delay-thou distinguished by the markings of thy head, whose generous paunch sways and whose belly droops with rolls of fat. And thou, the Eel-pout, who o'er Illyricum, o'er the marshes of twice-named2 Ister art betrayed and taken through tell-tale streaks of floating foam, hast been carried to our waters lest the glad streams of Moselle should be cheated of so famed a fosterling. With what colours has Nature painted thee! Above, dark spots pick out thy back, and rings of saffron surround them3 azure hue continues the length of thy sleek back3 up to the middle of thy length thou art full-fleshed and fat, but froin there right on to thy tail’s tip, thy skin is rough and dry.

115 Neither shalt thou, O Perch, the dainty of our tables, be unsung—thou amongst fishes river-born worthy to be ranked with the sea-bred, who alone canst vie on equal terms with the rosy mullet3 for not insipid is thy flavour, and in thy plump body the parts meet as segments, but are kept apart by the backbone.
